---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const post = postBySlug('flat-pack-assembly-ayr')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Flat-pack assembly',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'flat pack assembly Ayrshire', 'PAX wardrobe Ayr', 'IKEA assembly Ayr', 'furniture assembly KA7'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Ayr, Scotland' },
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="article"
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        A 200cm double PAX takes a competent pair of hands two to three hours.
        Here is the honest version of flat-pack pricing in Ayr, what we bring
        that IKEA’s own service does not, and why an uneven floor is the
        difference between a job and a mess.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/flat-pack-assembly/`}>Flat-pack assembly</a>
        looks like cheap work on paper. Two hundred pounds for something you
        could build yourself with an Allen key and an afternoon. In practice
        a PAX build is a three-hour job with a proper drill, a good level,
        two adults and wall fixings that are nowhere in the IKEA bag. Half
        our calls in <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a> for flat-pack are
        rescues from customers who have started and given up at the drawer
        runners.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is what it actually costs, what actually takes the time, and why
        a handyman who builds ten wardrobes a month is a different animal
        from IKEA’s own subcontracted assembly service.
      </p>

      <h2>How long a PAX really takes</h2>
      <p>
        A standard IKEA PAX — two 100cm frames, 200cm tall, with one
        fitted interior (say four shelves, one clothes rail, two drawers
        and a pair of sliding mirror doors) — takes me about two and a
        half hours from a sealed flat-pack to standing and wall-anchored
        in the bedroom. Single-handed it is closer to three hours because
        the frames are awkward to tip upright on your own.
      </p>
      <p>A rough breakdown of the time:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Unpacking and checking parts against the manifest — 10 minutes.</li>
        <li>Both frames built flat on the floor — 45 minutes.</li>
        <li>Interior fit-out (shelves, drawers, rail) — 30 minutes.</li>
        <li>Frames tipped upright and joined — 15 minutes.</li>
        <li>Wall-anchoring into the correct fixing for your wall — 15 minutes.</li>
        <li>Sliding doors hung and levelled — 25 minutes. This is where most DIY builds die.</li>
        <li>Packaging flattened and out of the house — 10 minutes.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Double the scale — a 250cm triple PAX with the platinum-glass sliding
        doors, three drawer banks and ten shelves — and you are looking at a
        full day for one person, or half a day for two.
      </p>

      <h2>Honest price bands for flat-pack in Ayr</h2>
      <p>
        We price by item type, not by the hour. Hourly quotes punish the
        customer for the moments where we stop to do it right. Typical Ayr
        prices:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>£40</strong> — small items. MALM bedside, LACK table, KALLAX 2×2, IKEA office chair. Usually under an hour on site.</li>
        <li><strong>£60–£80</strong> — mid-size. MALM 6-drawer chest, PLATSA single frame, desk with cable management, Argos sofa.</li>
        <li><strong>£80–£120</strong> — standard double PAX, KALLAX 4×4, B&Q fitted-wardrobe kit, larger sideboards. Includes wall-anchoring.</li>
        <li><strong>£120–£180</strong> — triple PAX with sliding doors, HEMNES double bed with storage, Wayfair L-shape desk units.</li>
        <li><strong>£180+</strong> — full room fit-outs, multiple items in one visit. Bundled.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We do not charge a call-out fee anywhere in Ayr, Prestwick, Troon or
        the rest of our <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>East Ayrshire patch</a>.
        The price quoted is the price paid. Written on WhatsApp before we
        arrive so there is no on-day surprise.
      </p>

      <h2>What we bring that IKEA’s own service doesn’t</h2>
      <p>
        IKEA’s in-house assembly (subcontracted through TaskRabbit in most of
        Scotland) is fine at building the thing as per the instructions.
        What it does not include — and what actually makes or breaks the
        finished job:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Proper wall fixings for your wall.</strong> The screws in
          the IKEA bag are for timber stud. Most Ayr bedrooms are on plaster
          over lath, dot-and-dab plasterboard, or solid masonry. Each one
          needs a different fixing — plasterboard anchors, metal plugs,
          proper masonry plugs with the right drill bit. We carry all of
          them.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>A proper stud detector.</strong> TaskRabbit pros have the
          kit; some do not. We always find the studs before we drill, and
          we anchor into stud where we can.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Shim packs for uneven floors.</strong> Half of Ayr has an
          older sandstone house with a floor that drops 12mm across a
          wardrobe footprint. Without shims, the sliding doors will not
          track. With shims, they do. We carry them.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>A second brain for the instructions.</strong> Most damage
          on a PAX build happens on page four where the hinge arm and the
          buffer get swapped. A handyman who has built ten wardrobes does
          not make that mistake.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Disposal.</strong> We flatten and take every scrap of
          packaging away. IKEA’s assembly does not.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The two things that ruin most DIY builds</h2>

      <h3>1. Wall fixings into dot-and-dab</h3>
      <p>
        A lot of Ayr new-builds and 1990s houses have plasterboard bonded
        onto masonry with plaster dabs — the “dot-and-dab” wall. If you drive
        a plain plug into that you hit a void an inch deep and the plug is
        doing nothing. Pull the PAX forward and the whole thing rips the
        fixing out. Dot-and-dab needs a deep-set fixing through to the
        masonry behind. We test every fixing point before we commit.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Uneven floors and sliding doors</h3>
      <p>
        PAX sliding doors will not run if the top and bottom tracks are even
        5mm out of level over 2m. Older Ayr houses — especially seafront
        and Alloway cottages — almost never have a level floor. You have to
        shim the frames before you fit the doors. If you fit the doors first
        and try to shim after, they will catch on the buffer and bounce
        back every time.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>

      <h3>Do you build all flat-pack, not just IKEA?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Wayfair, B&Q, Argos, Dunelm, Oak Furnitureland, Made.com legacy
        stock, JYSK, VonHaus — if it comes in a box, we build it. IKEA is
        just the most common because they sell the most.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I get a same-week slot?</h3>
      <p>
        For Ayr, almost always. Small single-item jobs same-day or next-day
        is normal. Triple-PAX full-room fits we usually slot in inside a
        week.
      </p>

      <h3>What if I am missing a part from the box?</h3>
      <p>
        Honestly, it happens more than IKEA admit. We carry a stock of
        common cam-locks, wooden dowels and screws. For genuinely unique
        parts we will reschedule and give you the IKEA phone number that
        actually gets a person — saves you an afternoon.
      </p>

      <h3>Do you dispose of the old furniture?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, for a small add-on. A single-item disposal (old wardrobe out,
        new one in) is usually £30 extra on top of the build price. We
        pay the tip fee.
      </p>

      <h3>Where exactly do you cover?</h3>
      <p>
        The whole of KA7 and KA9 — Ayr town centre, seafront, Alloway,
        Prestwick, Monkton — plus across to Troon. Further afield is fine
        too; see <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>our full coverage map</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Send Aidan a photo of the flat-pack box and your room. We will come
        back with a firm price and a slot within the hour.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />

  <CTABlock
    heading="PAX in a heap on the bedroom floor? We’ll sort it."
    sub="WhatsApp Aidan a photo of the box and the room — firm price back to you inside an hour, built same week across Ayr."
    location="Ayr"
  />
</BaseLayout>
